info.name: <html>
info.description: The <html> element represents the top-level of an HTML document and is referred to as the root element.

info.name: <head>
info.description: The <head> element contains machine-readable information (metadata) about the document, such as the title, <script> and <style> elements, and <meta> elements.

info.name: <meta>
info.description: The <meta> element represents metadata about the page used by the browser or search engines, including description, keywords, and character sets.

info.name: <title>
info.description: The <title> element sets the title of the document and exposes it to users via the UI of the browser or app they're using and through assistive technology.

info.name: <link>
info.description: The <link> element creates a relationship between the current document and an external resource, such as a stylesheet or favicon.

info.name: <script> and <noscript>
info.description: The <script> element contains or loads data or executable code. This is typically used to load JavaScript code. The <noscript> element represents alternative content to show when scripting is not allowed.

info.name: <body>
info.description: The <body> element represents the content of an HTML document.

info.name: <header> and <footer>
info.description: The <header> and <footer> HTML elements represent content that precedes and follows the main page content, respectively.

info.name: <div>
info.description: The <div> HTML element is the generic container for content.

info.name: <ol>, <ul>, and <li>
info.description: The <ol>, <ul>, and <li> HTML elements represent ordered and unordered lists.

info.name: <a>
info.description: The <a> element creates a hyperlink to any resource that's accessible via a URL, such as web pages, files, email addresses, or locations within the same page.

info.name: <span>
info.description: The <span> HTML element is the generic inline container for content.

info.name: <address>
info.description: The <address> element represents contact information for a person or people, or for an organization.
The element adds an image into the document.

info.name: <nav>
info.description: The <nav> element represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents.

info.name: <button>
info.description: The <button> HTML element represents a button that triggers some action, such as submitting a form or opening a dialog, styled as a labeled rectangular box by default.

info.name: <main>
info.description: The <main> element represents the dominant content of a document. It is commonly used together with <header> and <footer>.

info.name: <article>
info.description: The <article> element represents self-contained content, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable, such as a comment, a blog post, or news article.

info.name: <h1> through <h6>
info.description: The <h1> through <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings, in order of decreasing importance.

info.name: <section>
info.description: The <section> element is a generic standalone section of a document, which doesn't have a more specific semantic element to represent it.

info.name: <figure> and <figcaption>
info.description: The <figure> and <figcaption> HTML elements represent an illustration, diagram, text, or other self-contained reference content, with an optional caption.

The

element represents a paragraph of text.

info.name: <strong>
info.description: The <strong> HTML element brings attention to the content, styling text as bold by default.

info.name: JavaScript modules
info.description: JavaScript modules allow code to be organized into reusable units. Modules use import to load other modules and export to declare what is available to import from other modules. In HTML, modules are loaded with <script type="module">.

info.name: margin
info.description: The margin CSS property sets space around an element. It is a shorthand for margin-top, margin-right, margin-bottom, and margin-left.

info.name: padding
info.description: The padding CSS property sets space between an element's edge and its contents. It is a shorthand for padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, and padding-left.

info.name: box-sizing
info.description: The box-sizing CSS property sets whether an element's width and height are calculated based on the content-box, which does not count the size of borders or padding, or border-box, which does count them.

info.name: List style
info.description: The list-style shorthand CSS property and the list-style-image, list-style-position, and list-style-type longhand properties set the position and appearance of a list item's marker.

info.name: text-decoration
info.description: The text-decoration CSS property sets the style and color of decorative lines including underline, overline, line-through, or a combination of lines.

info.name: Display
info.description: The display CSS property sets the display behavior of an element's box within its layout and sets the layout behavior for its child elements.

info.name: Borders
info.description: The border CSS property sets the color, style, and width of the line around an element.

info.name: background
info.description: The background CSS property is a shorthand that sets several background properties at once.

info.name: Font shorthand
info.description: The font CSS property shorthand sets multiple font properties, including style, weight, size, and font family.

info.name: text-align
info.description: The text-align CSS property sets the horizontal placement of the inner content of a block element.

info.name: Cursor styles
info.description: The cursor CSS property styles the pointer, allowing you to provide hints to the user on how to interact with the hovered element.

info.name: font-style
info.description: The font-style CSS property sets the text style, with normal, italic, and oblique options.

info.name: Color
info.description: The color CSS property sets the primary foreground color of an element, which is used for text, the default border color, and text decorations.

info.name: pointer-events
info.description: The pointer-events CSS property sets whether a user can interact with an element using a mouse, touch, or other pointing input device.

info.name: font-family
info.description: The font-family CSS property sets the desired font face for text, along with optional fallback font faces.

info.name: scroll-behavior
info.description: The scroll-behavior CSS property controls whether scrolling is smooth or snaps, for scroll actions not performed by the user such as those triggered by navigation.

info.name: overflow
info.description: The overflow CSS property sets the behavior for when content doesn't fit in an element.

info.name: Width and height
info.description: The width and height CSS properties set the preferred physical size of an element.

info.name: Logical properties
info.description: CSS logical properties control borders, size, margin, and padding with directions and dimensions relative to the writing mode. For example, in a left to right, top to bottom writing mode, block-end refers to the bottom. Also known as flow relative.

info.name: Transitions (CSS)
info.description: The transition shorthand CSS property sets how changes to an element's styles may occur over time. Transitions can be applied to specific CSS properties, all properties, or none.

info.name: line-height
info.description: The line-height CSS property sets the spacing between text baselines, oriented to the horizontal or vertical writing mode.

info.name: font-size
info.description: The font-size CSS property sets the text height.

info.name: font-weight
info.description: The font-weight CSS property controls the thickness of a font. It is set explicitly with the keyword bold or a number, or relative to the inherited thickness with the keywords bolder or lighter.

info.name: Position
info.description: The position CSS property sets the origin position of an element to an element, the element's scrollport, or the viewport.

info.name: text-transform
info.description: The text-transform CSS property sets text case and capitalization.

info.name: z-index
info.description: The z-index CSS property orders overlapping elements, with higher values appearing in front of or on top of lower values.

info.name: Content
info.description: The content CSS property sets the content inside of an element or pseudo-element, replacing the current value. It's often used with the ::before and ::after pseudo-elements to generate cosmetic content.

info.name: Physical properties
info.description: The physical CSS properties, top, right, bottom, and left, set the inset position of an element relative to the corresponding side of a container determined by the element's position property.

info.name: border-radius
info.description: The border-radius CSS property rounds the corners of the border drawn around an element.

info.name: Flexbox
info.description: Flexbox is a one-dimensional layout system, which places content either horizontally or vertically, with optional wrapping.

info.name: Grid
info.description: CSS grid is a two-dimensional layout system, which lays content out in rows and columns.

info.name: Scroll snap
info.description: CSS scroll snap controls the panning and scrolling behavior within a scroll container.

info.name: Min and max width and height
info.description: The min-width, min-height, max-width, and max-height CSS properties set the minimum and maximum size of an element.

info.name: outline
info.description: The outline CSS shorthand sets the color, style, and width of a line around an element, outside of the border.

info.name: box-shadow
info.description: The box-shadow CSS property applies shadow effects around an element's frame. This can create drop shadow and inner shadow effects.

info.name: visibility
info.description: The visibility CSS property sets whether an element is shown. Invisible elements still affect the document layout.

info.name: 2D transforms
info.description: The transform CSS property and its 2D transform functions allow rotating, scaling, skewing, and translating an element. Arbitrary 2D transforms are also possible using a transformation matrix.

info.name: opacity
info.description: The opacity CSS property sets the transparency of an element.

info.name: aspect-ratio
info.description: The aspect-ratio CSS property controls the width-to-height ratio of elements. For and

info.name: object-fit
info.description: The object-fit CSS property sets how images, videos, and other replaced elements are scaled within their container.

info.name: all
info.description: The all CSS property is a shorthand for all CSS properties, except for direction and unicode-bidi. It accepts only the keywords for explicit defaulting (such as initial and inherit), since they are the only values supported on all CSS properties.

info.name: Multi-column layout
info.description: Multi-column layout flows an element's content across one or more columns in a single row, without affecting the display property of its children.

info.name: Animations (CSS)
info.description: The animation CSS property animates an element's style over time, using keyframes described in @keyframes rules.

info.name: Media queries
info.description: The @media CSS rule conditionally applies styles based on the output device type, its capabilities, and the user's preferences. Media queries are composed of an optional media type such as screen or print, and one or more mandatory media features, such as prefers-reduced-animations.

info.name: Page breaks
info.description: In printed page layouts, the break-after, break-before, break-inside CSS properties control where printed pages start and end. Also known as pagination or page breaking.

info.name: <i>
info.description: The <i> HTML element identifies idiomatic content, styling text as italic by default.

info.name: Events
info.description: The Event API and the addEventListener() method on objects that receive events (event targets) represent and handle significant things happening on a page. Many APIs fire events for a wide range of situations relating to those APIs, such as an image loading, a user clicking, or a value changing.

info.name: User activation
info.description: The navigator.userActivation API reveals whether the user has interacted with the page through an "activation" gesture such as a click, tap, or key press. User activation gated APIs (such as the fullscreen API) fail without user interaction, and this API allows you to predict such a failure.

info.name: DOM
info.description: The DOM (Document Object Model) API represents HTML and XML documents as trees of nodes. You can use the API to inspect and modify the structure and content of a document.

info.name: overlay
info.description: The overlay CSS property, used as an allow-discrete CSS transition, prevents a top layer element, such as a popover or a <dialog>, from being removed from the top layer before it has finished animating. You can't set the value of the overlay property; only use it as transition property.

info.name: Push messages
info.description: The Push API subscribes to and receives server-initiated messages. Subscribers receive pushed messages in the background, even after periods inactive or offline.

info.name: Window
info.description: The window global object represents a browser tab or iframe and its relationship to the document and other tabs. It's also a generic global object, under which many other APIs are located.

info.name: Scroll methods on elements
info.description: The scroll() and scrollBy() methods change the scroll position of overflow content within an element. Similar to setting scrollTop and scrollLeft properties, but with options setting whether the scroll should animate smoothly or jump. Note that scrollTo() is an alias for scroll().

info.name: Active view transition
info.description: The :active-view-transition CSS pseudo-class matches the root element when a view transition is active. The :active-view-transition-type() CSS pseudo-class matches only when the active view transition was started with the specified type.

info.name: white-space
info.description: The white-space CSS property sets how white space is collapsed and how lines wrap. It is a shorthand for white-space-collapse and text-wrap-mode.

info.name: Quotes
info.description: The quotes CSS property sets the quotation marks inserted via the content CSS property or <q> element.

info.name: vertical-align
info.description: The vertical-align CSS property sets the vertical alignment of inline, inline-block, and table cell elements. It has no effect on block-level elements.

info.name: Tables
info.description: The <table> HTML element, with several related elements, represents tabular data in rows and columns of cells.

info.name: text-shadow
info.description: The text-shadow CSS property sets the position and styles of shadow on text.

info.name: Page break aliases
info.description: The page-break-before, page-break-inside, and page-break-after CSS properties are aliases to the break-before, break-inside, and break-after properties.

info.name: Widows and orphans
info.description: The widows and orphans CSS properties set the minimum lines included in a text fragment created by page, column, or region breaks.

info.name: background-color
info.description: The background-color CSS property sets the fill color of an element, behind any content and background images or gradients.

info.name: Outlines
info.description: The outline-color, outline-style, and outline-width and outline-offset CSS properties style a line around an element, outside of the border.

info.name: clip
info.description: The clip CSS property sets the visible area of an absolutely positioned element.

info.name: float and clear
info.description: The float CSS property aligns an element to either side of its container, allowing text and inline elements to flow around it. The clear CSS property sets whether an element is moved below floating elements that proceed it.

info.name: Text overflow
info.description: The text-overflow CSS property sets how hidden overflow content appears to users. The property can clip content, truncate content with an ellipsis (…), or truncate with a custom string.

info.name: word-break
info.description: The word-break CSS property sets how lines break within words.

info.name: background-image
info.description: The background-image CSS property sets the graphics to display behind the content of an element and in front of the background color. Graphics may be any combination of images or gradients.

info.name: user-select
info.description: The user-select CSS property controls which elements can be selected by the user.

info.name: filter
info.description: The filter CSS property applies one or more graphic effects to an element. You can use filter functions, such as blur() and drop-shadow(), alone or combined to produce different effects.

info.name: background-clip
info.description: The background-clip CSS property sets the extent of the background: the padding box, the content box, or the default border box.

info.name: background-position
info.description: The background-position CSS property offsets the initial position of background images relative to the background origin.

info.name: background-size
info.description: The background-size CSS property scales or stretches a background based on the size of the element (with the contain and cover keywords), a length, or percentage.

info.name: zoom
info.description: The zoom CSS property scales the size of an element. Unlike the transform property, a zoomed element affects page layout.

info.name: background-repeat
info.description: The background-repeat CSS property sets how a background image is tiled.

info.name: text-indent
info.description: The text-indent CSS property sets the size of the empty space (indentation) at the beginning of lines in a text.

info.name: Page setup
info.description: The @page CSS at-rule sets the page-specific dimensions and margins for content such as printed documents, ebooks, or slides.

info.name: @font-face
info.description: The @font-face CSS at-rule creates a custom font-family value. The at-rule's descriptors set the font's name, source, and various display settings.

info.name: Explicit resource management
info.description: The using and await using declarations and the dispose and asyncDispose symbols manage the lifecycle of resources such as file handles and streams. The DisposableStack and AsyncDisposableStack objects can group, dispose, and coordinate dependencies between multiple disposable resources.

info.name: Anchor positioning
info.description: Anchor positioning places an element based on the position of another element. For example, you can place a tooltip next to the content it references.

info.name: <style>
info.description: The <style> element embeds an inline CSS stylesheet in a document.

info.name: JavaScript (initial core language support)
info.description: JavaScript is a programming language that runs in browsers, usually through the <script> element. JavaScript has changed over many years. This feature represents the oldest language features, such as built-in objects, statements, and operators. Also known as ECMAScript.

info.name: Media source
info.description: The MediaSource API is a custom data source for media elements commonly used for adaptive streaming. Also known as Media Source Extensions (MSE).

info.name: Navigation API
info.description: The navigation API initiates, intercepts, or modifies browser navigation actions. Not to be confused with the navigator API.

info.name: setTimeout()
info.description: The setTimeout() global function executes provided code after a given duration of time, and the accompanying clearTimeout() cancels the timer.

info.name: Alerts
info.description: The window.alert(), window.confirm(), and window.prompt() methods open modal dialogs for notifying the user, asking for confirmation, or entering text.

info.name: BroadcastChannel
info.description: The BroadcastChannel API allows you to send messages between same-origin browsing contexts, such as between the same page loaded in multiple tabs.

info.name: calc() keywords
info.description: The e, pi, infinity, and NaN keywords represent well-defined constants accepted in CSS math functions such as calc().

info.name: @supports
info.description: The @supports at-rule applies styles based on a browser's support for CSS features, such as a CSS property and value. Also known as feature queries.

info.name: attr()
info.description: The attr() CSS function, in the context of any property, returns the value of an attribute of an HTML element, with the option to return it as a specific type or unit. You can set a default value for missing or invalid attributes.

info.name: Constructed stylesheets
info.description: The CSSStyleSheet constructor creates a new stylesheet which can be shared between a document and multiple shadow roots using adoptedStyleSheets.

info.name: Sanitizer API
info.description: The Document.parseHTML() static method and the setHTML() method of Element and ShadowRoot objects parse and insert HTML into the DOM in a way that can prevent cross-site scripting attacks. The Sanitizer API can customize the sanitization process.

info.name: <select>
info.description: The <select> element provides a menu of options for a user to pick from, typically rendered as a dropdown list.

info.name: <data>
info.description: The <data> element links a given piece of content with a machine-readable translation.

info.name: Functions
info.description: Functions are series of statements that can be called and return a value. The function keyword (as in function () { }) and arrow (=>) expression create functions. The JavaScript functions protocol includes default and rest parameters and binding to this.

info.name: <b>
info.description: The <b> HTML element draws reader's attention to text, styling text as bold by default.

info.name: DOM Geometry
info.description: The DOMMatrix, DOMPoint, DOMQuad and DOMRect APIs represent points, rectangles, quadrilaterals and transformation matrices within JavaScript. They can be used in transformations in CSS, <canvas>, and SVG.

info.name: Web Audio
info.description: The Web Audio API creates graphs of audio nodes that handle sound inputs, synthesize sounds, apply effects, create visualizations, and output to audio devices.

info.name: WebNN
info.description: The WebNN API constructs and executes computational graphs of neural networks by making use of the various machine learning capabilities and hardware accelerators available on the device. Also known as Web Neural Network API.

info.name: <datalist>
info.description: The <datalist> element sets recommended values for an <input> element. Browsers may show a dropdown menu of all values or match values as the user types.

info.name: element()
info.description: The element() CSS function creates a live-updating image from an HTML element that can be used as an image or background image.

info.name: Geolocation
info.description: The navigator.gelocation API requests the user's latitude, longitude, heading, and speed.

info.name: <audio>
info.description: The <audio> element plays sound such as audio effects or music, optionally with controls provided by the browser.

info.name: Keyboard lock
info.description: The navigator.keyboard.lock() API allows you to capture keys that are normally reserved by the operating system. It can be used to provide an immersive fullscreen experience such as games.

info.name: Device orientation events
info.description: The DeviceMotion and DeviceOrientation events report the movement and orientation of the browser's device in physical space. Note that coordinates can differ noticeably between platforms and devices.

info.name: Selection
info.description: The Selection API controls and modifies user text selections within the page.

info.name: Back/forward cache blocking reasons
info.description: The notRestoredReasons property of a PerformanceNavigationTiming object explains why the current document was blocked from using the back/forward cache (also known as the bfcache) on navigation.

info.name: Gamepad VR hands and poses
info.description: The hand and pose properties of a Gamepad object represent the position in space and the hand that WebVR controllers are held in.

info.name: <dialog>
info.description: The <dialog> HTML element represents a modal or non-modal dialog box, such as a confirmation prompt or a subwindow used to enter data.

info.name: :dir()
info.description: The :dir() CSS functional pseudo-class matches elements by text direction, either right to left (rtl) or left to right (ltr).

info.name: Dedicated workers
info.description: The Worker() constructor runs a script in its own thread, which can send and receive messages with the script that created it. Also known as web workers.

info.name: <fencedframe>
info.description: The <fencedframe> element embeds another HTML page into the current page in a more secure and privacy-preserving way than <iframe> elements.

info.name: CSS object model
info.description: The CSS object model API reads, creates, and modifies CSS stylesheets and inline styles. Also known as CSSOM.

info.name: Array find() and findIndex()
info.description: The find() and findIndex() methods of arrays and typed arrays search an array for the first item that satisfies a test function.

info.name: box-decoration-break
info.description: The box-decoration-break CSS property sets whether box decorations, such as borders or backgrounds, of an element divided across a page, column, or region wraps each fragment or splits across the break.

info.name: Array (initial support)
info.description: Arrays are ordered lists of JavaScript values.

info.name: ::scroll-button
info.description: The ::scroll-button(<dir>) CSS pseudo-element is a focusable button which scrolls its originating scroll container element in the specified direction.

info.name: Async generators
info.description: Async generator functions (async function*) create iterators that return multiple promises, one after another, on-demand.

info.name: MediaController
info.description: The playback of multiple <video> or <audio> elements can be coordinated by a MediaController instance, for example to synchronize a sign-language interpreter track with the main video track.

info.name: Atomics.pause()
info.description: The Atomics.pause() static method gives a hint to the CPU that the code calling the method is in a short-duration wait for shared memory, known as spinning or a spinlock.

info.name: CloseWatcher
info.description: The CloseWatcher API listens and responds to close requests on in-page components, such as modals, popovers, and sidebars.

info.name: Console
info.description: The console API logs debugging messages to the browser development tools' console.

info.name: String (initial support)
info.description: The string type (and String object) represents a sequence of characters.

info.name: Accelerometer
info.description: The Accelerometer, LinearAccelerationSensor and GravitySensor APIs read the acceleration applied to a device in three dimensions, either including the effect of gravity, without its effect, or only its effect, respectively.

info.name: Array iteration methods
info.description: Array iteration methods

info.name: SVG
info.description: The SVG image format, represented by the <svg> element, creates two-dimensional vector graphics with declarative or scripted interaction and animation.

info.name: 3D transforms
info.description: The transform CSS property and its 3D transform functions allow rotations and other transforms in three dimensions, including perspective transforms.
